[3] USA (Staten Island, New York)
Date: Tue 11 Apr 2017 1:55 PM EDT
Source: Staten Island Live [edited]
http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2017/04/measles_scare_at_staten_island.html


If you have young children who attend daycare, or even school-aged kids, you know that getting unexpected letters home can be scary. And, it usually means your child is going to get sick because a virus or some illness is going around.

So you could imagine one Staten Island mother's reaction when she received a letter from her son's daycare that a child had been diagnosed with measles.

"A child in our infant group has been diagnosed with the measles. Since this child has a sibling in one of the older groups, and all preschool groups have been together for special events, we are sending the notice home Center wide," the letter from the College of Staten Island Children's Center read.

The mother posted a photo of the letter to a popular Staten Island parent Facebook page, outraged that a sick child was allowed to attend school. The post has since been taken down.

She also wondered how the child contracted measles, since vaccinations are typically a requirement to attend school and many daycare centers in New York.

The post received dozens of comments from concerned parents.

"Upon report of a single child on [Fri 7 Apr 2017] whose pediatrician thought might have the measles, the Center followed DOH (Department of Health) protocols and sent a letter home to all parents. Although this case of the measles is not confirmed, the Center will require a doctor's note indicating that the child is medically cleared to return to the Center. This is the Center's policy with any contagious illness," said Ken Bach, spokesman for the College of Staten Island.

Prior to receiving the phone call, the child had not been at the Center since [Mon 3 Apr 2017] after the child developed a low-grade fever and was picked up shortly thereafter, Bach told the Advance.

Bach said that the Center follows all Department of Health and Mental Hygiene [DOHMH] requirements "to ensure the health of all children who stay in the Center."

"All children with the Center are required to be up to date with their immunizations. The Center permits both of the DOH exemptions, a religious exemption or a medical exemption. Should a child with an exemption for a specific disease be registered with the Center when a case of that disease is reported, that child will not be able to participate in the program for a minimum of 2 weeks," Bach said in a statement to the Advance.

The post created an uproar and re-ignited the ongoing vaccination debate.

In another post on the Facebook page, a parent stated her anger that some parents bring their sick children to school or do not pick them up when they are sick, letting them sit in the nurse's office or in class until the end of the day.

"Sometimes kids are contagious before they are outwardly sick...," stated one parent, arguing that, like the measles, children can be contagious for days before they show any symptoms.

Another parent said that there is no excuse for sending a sick child to school: "If your child is sick you should keep him or her home. It's unfair that because you may have work that my child gets your kid's germs. We should be considerate of people's lives but what about being considerate about getting other children sick?"

Other parents were more understanding. "Kids get germs from everywhere. Not everyone is lucky enough to be able to choose between work and staying home. I always had someone do it so it was easier for us but I do feel bad for people who have no choice," another woman posted on the comment thread.

Then, the vaccination debate began.

While it is a requirement for children who want to attend school and daycare centers in New York, there are a religious and medical exemptions to the vaccination mandate.

Additionally, children under the age of 1 are not required to receive the vaccination to attend.

In a shared space daycare that is occupied by infants who have not received the vaccination, who may have been exposed to the illness, and older children who have received the vaccination, contracting a disease is not difficult.

The DOHMH requires that pre-kindergarten students, including daycare, Head Start, and nursery school students receive at least 1 of the 2 doses of the measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccine in order to attend.

Kindergarten through 12th grade and college require both doses.

The vaccination schedule states that children get 2 doses of the MMR vaccination; the 1st dose is given between 12-15 months old and the 2nd dose is given between 4-6 years old, according to the Center for Disease Control (CDC) website.

As with any vaccination, the MMR poses some risk and side effects are possible.

The CDC says that fever occurs in 1 out of 6 cases; a mild rash occurs in 1 out of 20 and swollen glands in the cheek or neck in 1 out of 75 within 6-14 days of receiving the vaccine.

More uncommon reactions to the vaccine include seizure, in 1 out of 3000; temporary pain or stiffness in the joints, in 1 out of 4, and temporary low platelet count, which can cause a bleeding disorder, in 1 out of 30 000 cases.

